events.originalText: The passenger ferry MV Rabaul Queen capsized and sank in rough conditions in the Solomon Sea, resulting in at least 88 deaths.
events.subtitle: MV Rabaul Queen
events.headline: MV Rabaul Queen Capsizes in Solomon Sea, 88 Dead

events.originalText: Omid, Iran's first domestically made satellite, was successfully launched from Semnan Space Center.
events.subtitle: Omid
events.headline: Iran's First Satellite Omid Launched Successfully

events.originalText: Following a Derby di Sicilia match in Catania, football violence caused the death of police officer Filippo Raciti, leading to new safety regulations at Italian sporting events.
events.subtitle: Derby di Sicilia
events.headline: Football Violence in Catania Leads to Death of Officer Raciti

events.originalText: Swiss tennis player Roger Federer became the top-ranked men's singles player, a position he held for a record 237 consecutive weeks.
events.subtitle: Roger Federer
events.headline: Roger Federer Becomes Top-Ranked Men's Singles Player

events.originalText: The F-16 Fighting Falcon (pictured), the most numerous fixed-wing aircraft currently in military service, made its first flight.
events.subtitle: General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon
events.headline: F-16 Fighting Falcon Makes First Flight

events.originalText: Protestors burned the British Embassy in Ireland following the massacre of 14 civilians in Derry by British forces.
events.subtitle: Burning of the British Embassy in Dublin
events.headline: Protestors Burn British Embassy in Ireland

events.originalText: 113 alleged communists were arrested and detained without trial by Singapore's security agencies.
events.subtitle: Operation Coldstore
events.headline: 113 Alleged Communists Arrested in Singapore

events.originalText: World War II: The Soviet Red Army captured 91,000 tired and starving German soldiers, ending the Battle of Stalingrad, one of the bloodiest battles in human history.
events.subtitle: World War II
events.headline: Soviet Red Army Captures 91,000 German Soldiers at Stalingrad

events.originalText: The first act of the Norwegian resistance movement took place with the bombing of Oslo East Station by the Osvald Group to protest the inauguration of Vidkun Quisling.
events.subtitle: Norwegian resistance movement
events.headline: Norwegian Resistance Movement Begins with Oslo Bombing

events.originalText: The Export–Import Bank of the United States, the country's official export credit agency, was established.
events.subtitle: Export–Import Bank of the United States
events.headline: Export-Import Bank of the United States Established

events.originalText: The signing of the Treaty of Tartu ended the Estonian War of Independence, with Soviet Russia agreeing to recognize the country's independence and renounce in perpetuity all rights to its territory.
events.subtitle: Treaty of Tartu (Estonia–Russia)
events.headline: Treaty of Tartu Ends Estonian War of Independence

events.originalText: New York City's Grand Central Terminal, the world's largest train station by number of platforms, opened immediately after midnight.
events.subtitle: Grand Central Terminal
events.headline: Grand Central Terminal Opens in New York City

events.originalText: Ute Wars: Brigham Young announced his decision to go to war against the Timpanogos, who were hostile to the Mormon settlement at Fort Utah.
events.subtitle: Ute Wars
events.headline: Brigham Young Declares War Against Timpanogos

events.originalText: Scottish sailor Alexander Selkirk was rescued by English captain Woodes Rogers and his crew after spending four years as a castaway on an uninhabited island in the Pacific, providing the inspiration for Daniel Defoe's novel Robinson Crusoe.
events.subtitle: Alexander Selkirk
events.headline: Castaway Alexander Selkirk Rescued After Four Years

events.originalText: Jan van Riebeeck, the founder of Cape Town, produced the first bottle of South African wine (vineyard pictured).
events.subtitle: Jan van Riebeeck
events.headline: Jan van Riebeeck Produces First South African Wine

events.originalText: Nine leaders of the Transylvanian peasant revolt were executed at Torda.
events.subtitle: Transylvanian peasant revolt
events.headline: Transylvanian Revolt Leaders Executed at Torda

events.originalText: Alaric II, King of the Visigoths, promulgated a collection of Roman law known as the Breviary of Alaric.
events.subtitle: Alaric II
events.headline: King Alaric II Promulgates Breviary of Alaric
